    "description": "Cicero describes the villa of Publius Clodius Pulcher as being located at the thirteenth mile of the Via Appia near Bovillae.",
    "details": "<p><em>The Barrington Atlas Directory</em> notes: Clodio, so-called Villa of Clodius. Research conducted by Aarhus University ca. 2018 at the 13th mile of the Via Appia offered new interpretations of the archaeological remains on the grounds of the Villa S. Caterina at Castelgandolfo. These remains, based at least in part on Cicero, have traditionally been ascribed to a villa owned by Publius Clodius Pulcher. The more recent interpretation suggests that the remains here studied and published in the 19th and 20th centuries by Antonio Nibby, Luigi Canina, and Giuseppe Lugli might be attributable to a sanctuary of the <em>Bona Dea</em>.</p>",
